snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident Tragedy LIVE | Pune Horror : Do Rich Brats Get Away With Murder? | News18
snippet.description:
Pune Porsche Accident Tragedy LIVE | Pune Horror : Do Rich Brats Get Away With Murder? | News18

The furore over a Pune court letting the teen accused off the hook in the Porsche car crash that killed two software engineers has put the Juvenile Justice Board to test on whether the 17-year-old should be tried as an adult in the case.

The teen was driving drunk, beyond the permissible limit as per the law, at over 160 kmph, as per the police reports, and had confessed that his father, Vishal Agarwal, a prominent builder, knew about it.

Agarwal was arrested on Tuesday, since the accused is a minor, under sections 75 and 77 that deal will “willful neglect of a child” and supplying a child with “intoxicating liquor or drugs”.

snippet.title: Drunk Pune teen kills with Porsche: Why was 17-year old given keys to 'killing machine'|#SnapOpinion
snippet.description:
In a tragic case, two 24-year-old software engineers were killed by a Porsche car in Pune at around 2:30 AM on Sunday morning. The Porsche was being driven by a minor, who was out celebrating the end of his twelfth boards. On his way home, while drunk, he lost control of the car and ended two lives. The driver is reportedly the son of a wealthy Pune realtor, which seems to reflect in the court’s bail conditions for him. In this particular case, the 17 and a half year old had to write an essay on the accident and now has to “work with traffic police for 15 days.” There should be stricter laws to not only discourage underage drinking and driving, but also address such lapses in institutional justice — where the make of the car you’re driving can have a direct impact on the punishment for driving it drunk.

snippet.title: Pune Porsche Accident: Teen Crashes Porsche, Gets Bail In Less Than 24 hours I Pune Juvenile Court
snippet.description:
Pune Porsche Accident: Teen Crashes Porsche, Gets Bail In Less Than 24 hours 


Pune Car Crash Update: A Teen driver who recently caused a fatal crash in Pune, resulting in the deaths of two motorcyclists, was released on bail just 15 hours after the accident. When Pune police produced the minor in front of the magistrate, they requested the court to treat him as an adult. However, the request was rejected and the court granted bail under the Juvenile Justice Act, imposing a few conditions along with the bail. 

The accident took place around 3.15 am in Kalyani Nagar when a group of friends after a party at a restaurant in the area was returning home on their motorbikes. Near the Kalyani Nagar junction, a speeding luxury car hit one of the motorcycles following which its two riders fell from the vehicle and died on the spot, as per the FIR.

Several conditions were imposed on Juvenile driver release:

- Working alongside traffic police for 15 days.
- Undergoing psychiatric evaluation and treatment.
- Writing a 300-word essay on the "effect of road accidents and their solution".
- Seeking rehabilitation at a de-addiction centre.
- Studying traffic rules and giving a presentation on the same to the Juvenile Justice Board.
- Assisting accident victims in the future, if he witnesses one.
